children.subject: this semester the disparity is pretty large (bc ramchandran is such a good lecturer) but it seemed to be like this last fall too

I am in ee127 rn and I can tell you that without a solid math foundation taking this class is not very fun. I would strongly suggest reviewing your linear algebra and multivariable calculus before attempting it. There are only 3 GSIs for like 200 students right now, and the lectures and provided resources do not really help you with HW which is quite difficult unless you are have a strong math background.

this doesn't completely answer your question, but as a current student in both who also knows folks who took these classes last semester: don't overlook the "ergonomics" of the courses. 126 seems to be run far better (more discussion sections, more TA OHs, lecture content is clear, more support for students on Piazza) than 127 (feels like the instructor is freestyling in lecture, much fewer OH, ambiguous course policies that were not corrected until students raised the issue).

history.content: If you got an A+ in both 16b and 70 you should be fine for both classes. 127 may actually be more useful for Prof. Sahai's brand of 189 which has an early and heavy focus on various least squares formulations but I'm really just guessing here. I personally enjoyed 126 way more but since you stated you didn't really like probability in 70 you should aim for 127.

Can anybody speak as to the relative difficulty, real-world applications (in industry), interestingness, and workload of EECS 126 vs 127? As for the prereqs, I liked the material in 16b better than that of 70 (specifically the probability part), but I did equally well in both classes (A+). I plan on taking 189. I've read that 126 is supposedly better prep for 189, but I feel like I'll enjoy the material in 127 more. I only have space in my schedule for one of the two as of now. Which one should I take? Also, will 127 be offered in the fall/what's the likelihood of that happening (since no one knows for sure rn I think)?
